[2] Bolivia
Date: Mon 12 Mar 2007
From: Elaine Stevenson <elaine.stevenson@yahoo.com>
Source: El Dario.com (Cochabamba, Bolivia) [trans.Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.lostiempos.com/noticias/12-03-07/12_03_07_inter2.php>

Facing the climatic consequences of the El Nino phenomenon, the
Ministry of Health is reinforcing its intensive preventive sanitary
plan to avoid epidemics in those areas affected by the floods.
The epidemiological map of the Ministry of Health shows that at the
national level, there have been 634 dengue cases with one death from
DHF, 4 cases of yellow fever 3 cases of hantavirus [infection], 32
confirmed and 800 suspected cases of leptospirosis in Chuquisaca.
Of the 634 cases positive for dengue fever, 5 were reported from
Cochabamba, 585 from Santa Cruz, one from Tarija, 4 from Chuquisaca,
one from Potosi, and 38 from the Beni.
The Ministry of Health appropriated 300 000 Bolivianos [equivalent to
nearly USD 39 000. - Mod.TY] for dengue control in the regions
affected by the transmission [of the virus] by the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
The Epidemiological Unit prepared an insecticide fumigation [program]
for the destruction of mosquito breeding sites. This action will be
accompanied by information, education, and orientation [of the
public] in order to eliminate [mosquito] breeding sites and improve sanitation.
The Minister of Health, Nila Heredia, ... cited the cooperation of
Cuba, Chile, Argentina, USA, and Japan. Spain donated 6 sets of
emergency medical equipment and supplies, which have been distributed
to Santa Cruz (2), Beni (2), Tarija (one) and Cochabamba (one).
"The best way to avoid the arrival of dengue is to dry puddles where
the _Anopheles_ mosquitoes reproduce," she added. [Surely she meant
elimination of water catchments where _Aedes aegypti_ breeds, since
_Anopheles spp._ are not dengue virus vectors. Perhaps she was
misquoted. - Mod.TY]
--
