[5] Uruguay - ex Paraguay
Date: Sat 17 Mar 2007
From: Dan Silver <dgsilver@yahoo.com>
Source: La Prensa Digital (Argentina) [trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.laprensa.com.ar/secciones/nota.asp?ed=2358&tp=11&no=76354>

The [detection] of the 1st dengue case on Thursday [15 Mar 2007] has
provoked a psychological reaction in the Montevideo population, which
has gone to pharmacies to buy [insect] repellents, creams, and
antibiotics against the disease, according to sources from the area.
Also, the telephones of emergency medical [services] and a line to
the Ministry of Public Health have been swamped with calls for advice
and to complain about the presence in the city of the mosquito _Aedes
aegypti_, vector of the disease [virus].
On Thursday [15 Mar 2007] the 1st case of dengue was confirmed in the
country in a 40-year-old employee of a ground cargo transport
[company], who had been in Paraguay. On Wednesday [14 Mar 2007]
larvae of _Aedes aegypti_ were detected in a neighborhood in the
outskirts of the Uruguayan capital.
The officials of the Montevideo municipal government yesterday [16
Mar 2007] began a house-by-house inspection in the Villa Espanola
neighborhood, where _Aedes aegypti_ larvae were found, with the goal
of elimination of [water] containers that favor the reproduction of
this mosquito.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[There is considerable international cross-border land traffic among
the Southern Cone countries, so it is not surprising that dengue
virus infections acquired in countries in which dengue virus
transmission is going on currently become ill in their dengue-free
home country, as in this case. - Mod.TY]
