[6] Uruguay - local acquisition
Date: Mon 19 Mar 2007
From: Dan Silver <dgsilver@yahoo.com>
Source: People's Daily online, Xinhua Agency report [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200703/19/eng20070319_358975.html>

Uruguay's health authorities on Sunday [18 Mar 2007] confirmed the
country's 1st case of domestically caught dengue fever, by a
30-year-old man living in Salto, a city 500 km. (310 miles) from the
capital, Montevideo.
Jorge Basso, director of the National Health Service, told reporters
that definitive results are still 4 to 5 days away, but the patient
was been admitted to a Salto clinic and protected with mosquito nets
to prevent a wider outbreak of dengue, spread by the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
Uruguay will now apply Phase One of its plan to fight dengue, an
epidemic that has killed 20 and is affecting neighboring Brazil and
Argentina, and nearby Paraguay and Bolivia.
Beginning early Monday [26 Mar 2007], the authorities will fumigate
Salto, a city with a population of 100 000 people on the banks of the
Uruguay River, which marks the border with Argentina.
The authorities are also studying 2 other patients who may have the
disease and are under observation in Montevideo clinics.
The mosquito that transmits dengue had been eliminated from Uruguay
in 1958, but reappeared in 1997, as part of a spread across South
America that began in the 1980s.
--
