[7] Brazil
Date: Fri 9 Mar 2007
From: Elaine Stevenson <elaine.stevenson@yahoo.com>
Source: Unionradio.net de Caracas, Venezuela, Agencia EFE report
[trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.unionradio.com.ve/Noticias/Noticia.aspx?noticiaid=196885>

A dengue epidemic concentrated in the east-central region of Brazil
left today [9 Mar 2007] its 8th fatal victim in the state of Mato
Grosso do Sul, on the border with Paraguay and Bolivia. The
[government] authorities call for redoubling of preventive action in
the population.
Data from the Ministry of Health released today [9 Mar 2007] (current
as of 24 Feb [2007]) revealed that in the country there have been 67
847 [dengue] cases, of which 44 067 were in Mato Grosso do Sul, an
agricultural and livestock state with a small [human] population.
The Ministry indicated that up to [date] there have been 5 deaths
officially attributed to dengue hemorrhagic fever [DHF].
Of the total cases in Mato Grosso do Sul, 31 000 were concentrated in
the capital, Campo Grande, which, according to municipal officials,
is facing the worst [dengue] epidemic in its history, with 500 new
[dengue cases] reported per day.
DHF has caused 8 deaths in Mato Grosso, but these figures are [still]
subject to laboratory confirmation, according to local authorities.
Preliminary data from the Ministry of Health indicate that there were
345 922 dengue cases in 2006, with 78 percent occurring between the
months of January and May, which corresponds to the rainy season in
most of the country. In 2006, there were 628 confirmed cases DHF
[cases], with 67 deaths.
